# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sankey-diagrams
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sankey-diagrams/alluvial-diagram] In an alluvial diagram, blocks represent clusters of nodes, and stream fields between the blocks represent changes in the composition of these clusters over time.
[src:sankey-diagrams/alluvial-diagram] The height of a block represents the size of the cluster and the height of a stream field represents the size of the components contained in both blocks connected by the stream field.
[src:sankey-diagrams/alluvial-diagram] Alluvial diagrams were originally developed to visualize structural change in large complex networks.
[src:sankey-diagrams/alluvial-diagram] They can be used to visualize any type of change in group composition between states or over time and include statistical information to reveal significant change.
[src:sankey-diagrams/alluvial-diagram] Alluvial diagrams highlight important structural changes that can be further emphasized by color, and make identification of major transitions easy.
[src:sankey-diagrams/alluvial-diagram] Alluvial diagrams can also be used to illustrate patterns of flow on a fixed network over time.
[src:sankey-diagrams/alluvial-diagram] The *Users Flow* feature of Google Analytics uses alluvial diagrams to graphically represent how visitors move among the nodes (individual pages) on a website.
[src:sankey-diagrams/directed-graph] In mathematics, and more specifically in graph theory, a **directed graph** (or **digraph**) is a graph that is made up of a set of vertices connected by directed edges, often called **arcs**.
[src:sankey-diagrams/directed-graph] It differs from an ordinary or undirected graph, in that the latter is defined in terms of unordered pairs of vertices, which are usually called *edges*, *links* or *lines*.
[src:sankey-diagrams/directed-graph] The aforementioned definition does not allow a directed graph to have multiple arrows with the same source and target nodes, but some authors consider a broader definition that allows directed graphs to have such multiple arcs (namely, they allow the arc set to be a multiset).
[src:sankey-diagrams/directed-graph] Sometimes these entities are called **directed multigraphs** (or **multidigraphs**).
[src:sankey-diagrams/directed-graph] On the other hand, the aforementioned definition allows a directed graph to have loops (that is, arcs that directly connect nodes with themselves), but some authors consider a narrower definition that does not allow directed graphs to have loops.
[src:sankey-diagrams/directed-graph] Directed graphs without loops may be called **simple directed graphs**, while directed graphs with loops may be called *loop-digraphs* (see section Types of directed graph).
[src:sankey-diagrams/directed-graph] An arc (*x*, *y*) is considered to be directed *from* *x* *to* *y*; *y* is called the *head* and *x* is called the *tail* of the arc; *y* is said to be a *direct successor* of *x* and *x* is said to be a *direct predecessor* of *y*.
[src:sankey-diagrams/directed-graph] If a path leads from *x* to *y*, then *y* is said to be a *successor* of *x* and *reachable* from *x*, and *x* is said to be a *predecessor* of *y*.
[src:sankey-diagrams/directed-graph] The arc (*y*, *x*) is called the *reversed arc* of (*x*, *y*).
[src:sankey-diagrams/directed-graph] The adjacency matrix of a multidigraph with loops is the integer-valued matrix with rows and columns corresponding to the vertices, where a nondiagonal entry *a**ij* is the number of arcs from vertex *i* to vertex *j*, and the diagonal entry *a**ii* is the number of loops at vertex *i*.
[src:sankey-diagrams/directed-graph] The adjacency matrix of a directed graph is a logical matrix, and is unique up to permutation of rows and columns.
[src:sankey-diagrams/directed-graph] Another matrix representation for a directed graph is its incidence matrix.
[src:sankey-diagrams/directed-graph] For a vertex, the number of head ends adjacent to a vertex is called the *indegree* of the vertex and the number of tail ends adjacent to a vertex is its *outdegree* (called *branching factor* in trees).
[src:sankey-diagrams/directed-graph] The indegree of *v* is denoted deg−(*v*) and its outdegree is denoted deg+(*v*).
[src:sankey-diagrams/directed-graph] A vertex with deg−(*v*) = 0 is called a *source*, as it is the origin of each of its outgoing arcs.
[src:sankey-diagrams/directed-graph] Similarly, a vertex with deg+(*v*) = 0 is called a *sink*, since it is the end of each of its incoming arcs.
[src:sankey-diagrams/directed-graph] If for every vertex *v* ∈ *V*, deg+(*v*) = deg−(*v*), the graph is called a *balanced directed graph*.
[src:sankey-diagrams/directed-graph] The degree sequence of a directed graph is the list of its indegree and outdegree pairs; for the above example we have degree sequence ((2, 0), (2, 2), (0, 2), (1, 1)).
[src:sankey-diagrams/directed-graph] The degree sequence is a directed graph invariant so isomorphic directed graphs have the same degree sequence.
[src:sankey-diagrams/directed-graph] However, the degree sequence does not, in general, uniquely identify a directed graph; in some cases, non-isomorphic digraphs have the same degree sequence.
[src:sankey-diagrams/directed-graph] The directed graph realization problem is the problem of finding a directed graph with the degree sequence a given sequence of positive integer pairs.
[src:sankey-diagrams/directed-graph] This problem can either be solved by the Kleitman–Wang algorithm or by the Fulkerson–Chen–Anstee theorem.
[src:sankey-diagrams/directed-graph] A directed graph is *weakly connected* (or just *connected*) if the undirected *underlying graph* obtained by replacing all directed edges of the graph with undirected edges is a connected graph.
[src:sankey-diagrams/directed-graph] A directed graph is *strongly connected* or *strong* if it contains a directed path from *x* to *y* (and from *y* to *x*) for every pair of vertices (*x*, *y*).
[src:sankey-diagrams/directed-graph] The *strong components* are the maximal strongly connected subgraphs.
[src:sankey-diagrams/directed-graph] A connected rooted graph (or *flow graph*) is one where there exists a directed path to every vertex from a distinguished *root vertex*.
[src:sankey-diagrams/flow-diagram] Flow diagrams are used to structure and order a complex system, or to reveal the underlying structure of the elements and their interaction.
[src:sankey-diagrams/flow-diagram] The term flow diagram is used in theory and practice in different meanings.
[src:sankey-diagrams/flow-diagram] Most commonly the flow chart and flow diagram are used in an interchangeable way in the meaning of a representation of a process.
[src:sankey-diagrams/flow-diagram] ... is a diagram that visually displays interrelated information such as events, steps in a process, functions, etc., in an organized fashion, such as sequentially or chronologically.
[src:sankey-diagrams/flow-diagram] [is] a graphic representation of the physical route or flow of people, materials, paperworks, vehicles, or communication associated with a process, procedure plan, or investigation.
[src:sankey-diagrams/flow-diagram] In the second definition the meaning is limited to the representation of the physical route or flow.
[src:sankey-diagrams/flow-diagram] An example of such a diagram is the illustration of the flows in a nuclear submarine propulsion system, which shows different streams back and forth in the system.
[src:sankey-diagrams/flow-diagram] The representation of such a system can be supplemented by one or more flowcharts, which show the sequence of one of the flows in one direction, or any of the control flows to manage the system.
[src:sankey-diagrams/flow-diagram] The physical movement of objects from one location to another can also be visualized in a mix of maps and flowchart or sankey diagram, which are called flow maps.
[src:sankey-diagrams/flow-diagram] Flow maps can indicate on a map, what flows, moves or migrates, in which direction, and in which quantities etc.
[src:sankey-diagrams/graph-drawing] A drawing of a graph or **network diagram** is a pictorial representation of the vertices and edges of a graph.
[src:sankey-diagrams/graph-drawing] This drawing should not be confused with the graph itself: very different layouts can correspond to the same graph.
[src:sankey-diagrams/graph-drawing] In the abstract, all that matters is which pairs of vertices are connected by edges.
[src:sankey-diagrams/graph-drawing] In the concrete, however, the arrangement of these vertices and edges within a drawing affects its understandability, usability, fabrication cost, and aesthetics.
[src:sankey-diagrams/graph-drawing] The problem gets worse if the graph changes over time by adding and deleting edges (dynamic graph drawing) and the goal is to preserve the user's mental map.
[src:sankey-diagrams/graph-drawing] Graphs are frequently drawn as node–link diagrams in which the vertices are represented as disks, boxes, or textual labels and the edges are represented as line segments, polylines, or curves in the Euclidean plane.
[src:sankey-diagrams/graph-drawing] Node–link diagrams can be traced back to the 14th-16th century works of Pseudo-Lull which were published under the name of Ramon Llull, a 13th century polymath.
[src:sankey-diagrams/graph-drawing] Pseudo-Lull drew diagrams of this type for complete graphs in order to analyze all pairwise combinations among sets of metaphysical concepts.
[src:sankey-diagrams/graph-drawing] In the case of directed graphs, arrowheads form a commonly used graphical convention to show their orientation; however, user studies have shown that other conventions such as tapering provide this information more effectively.
[src:sankey-diagrams/graph-drawing] Upward planar drawing uses the convention that every edge is oriented from a lower vertex to a higher vertex, making arrowheads unnecessary.
[src:sankey-diagrams/graph-drawing] Many different quality measures have been defined for graph drawings, in an attempt to find objective means of evaluating their aesthetics and usability.
[src:sankey-diagrams/graph-drawing] In addition to guiding the choice between different layout methods for the same graph, some layout methods attempt to directly optimize these measures.
[src:sankey-diagrams/graph-drawing] In addition, the placement and routing steps of electronic design automation (EDA) are similar in many ways to graph drawing, as is the problem of greedy embedding in distributed computing, and the graph drawing literature includes several results borrowed from the EDA literature.
[src:sankey-diagrams/graph-drawing] There are many algorithms for graph drawing.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] The **nested set model** is a technique for representing nested set collections (also known as trees or hierarchies) in relational databases.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] It is based on Nested Intervals, that "are immune to hierarchy reorganization problem, and allow answering ancestor path hierarchical queries algorithmically — without accessing the stored hierarchy relation".
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] The standard relational algebra and relational calculus, and the SQL operations based on them, are unable to express directly all desirable operations on hierarchies.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] The nested set model is a solution to that problem.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] An alternative solution is the expression of the hierarchy as a parent-child relation.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] Joe Celko called this the adjacency list model.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] If the hierarchy can have arbitrary depth, the adjacency list model does not allow the expression of operations such as comparing the contents of hierarchies of two elements, or determining whether an element is somewhere in the subhierarchy of another element.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] When the hierarchy is of fixed or bounded depth, the operations are possible, but expensive, due to the necessity of performing one relational join per level.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] This is often known as the bill of materials problem.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] Hierarchies may be expressed easily by switching to a graph database.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] When these solutions are not available or not feasible, another approach must be taken.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] The nested set model is to number the nodes according to a tree traversal, which visits each node twice, assigning numbers in the order of visiting, and at both visits.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] This leaves two numbers for each node, which are stored as two attributes.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] Querying becomes inexpensive: hierarchy membership can be tested by comparing these numbers.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] Updating requires renumbering and is therefore expensive.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] Refinements that use rational numbers instead of integers can avoid renumbering, and so are faster to update, although much more complicated.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] The "Clothing" category, with the highest position in the hierarchy, encompasses all subordinating categories.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] It is therefore given left and right domain values of 1 and 22, the latter value being the double of the total number of nodes being represented.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] The next hierarchical level contains "Men's" and "Women's", both containing levels within themselves that must be accounted for.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] Each level's data node is assigned left and right domain values according to the number of sublevels contained within, as shown in the table data.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] Queries using nested sets can be expected to be faster than queries using a stored procedure to traverse an adjacency list, and so are the faster option for databases which lack native recursive query constructs, such as MySQL 5.x.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] However, recursive SQL queries can be expected to perform comparably for 'find immediate descendants' queries, and much faster for other depth search queries, and so are the faster option for databases which provide them, such as PostgreSQL, Oracle, and Microsoft SQL Server.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] MySQL used to lack recursive query constructs but added such features in version 8.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] The use case for a dynamic endless database tree hierarchy is rare.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] The Nested Set model is appropriate where the tree element and one or two attributes are the only data, but is a poor choice when more complex relational data exists for the elements in the tree.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] Given an arbitrary starting depth for a category of 'Vehicles' and a child of 'Cars' with a child of 'Mercedes', a foreign key table relationship must be established unless the tree table is natively non-normalized.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] Attributes of a newly created tree item may not share all attributes with a parent, child or even a sibling.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] If a foreign key table is established for a table of 'Plants' attributes, no integrity is given to the child attribute data of 'Trees' and its child 'Oak'.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] Therefore, in each case of an item inserted into the tree, a foreign key table of the item's attributes must be created for all but the most trivial of use cases.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] For more complex systems, hierarchy can be developed through relational models rather than an implicit numeric tree structure.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] Depth of an item is simply another attribute rather than the basis for an entire DB architecture.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] The model doesn't allow for multiple parent categories.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] For example, an 'Oak' could be a child of 'Tree-Type', but also 'Wood-Type'.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] An additional tagging or taxonomy has to be established to accommodate this, again leading to a design more complex than a straightforward fixed model.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] Nested sets are very slow for inserts because it requires updating left and right domain values for all records in the table after the insert.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] This can cause a lot of database stress as many rows are rewritten and indexes rebuilt.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] However, if it is possible to store a forest of small trees in table instead of a single big tree, the overhead may be significantly reduced, since only one small tree must be updated.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] The nested interval model does not suffer from this problem, but is more complex to implement, and is not as well known.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] It still suffers from the relational foreign-key table problem.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] The nested interval model stores the position of the nodes as rational numbers expressed as quotients (n/d).
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] Using the nested set model as described above has some performance limitations during certain tree traversal operations.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] The query will be more complicated when searching for children more than one level deep.
[src:sankey-diagrams/nested-set-model] To overcome this limitation and simplify tree traversal an additional column is added to the model to maintain the depth of a node within a tree.
[src:sankey-diagrams/sankey-diagram] Sankey diagrams can also visualize the energy accounts, material flow accounts on a regional or national level, and cost breakdowns.
[src:sankey-diagrams/sankey-diagram] The diagrams are often used in the visualisation of material flow analysis.
[src:sankey-diagrams/sankey-diagram] Sankey diagrams emphasize the major transfers or flows within a system.
[src:sankey-diagrams/sankey-diagram] They help locate the most important contributions to a flow.
[src:sankey-diagrams/sankey-diagram] They often show conserved quantities within defined system boundaries.
[src:sankey-diagrams/sankey-diagram] Sankey diagrams are named after Irish Captain Matthew Henry Phineas Riall Sankey, who used this type of diagram in 1898 in a classic figure (see diagram) showing the energy efficiency of a steam engine.
[src:sankey-diagrams/sankey-diagram] The original charts in black and white displayed just one type of flow (e.g., steam); using colors for different types of flows lets the diagram express additional variables.
[src:sankey-diagrams/sankey-diagram] Over time, it became a standard model used in science and engineering to represent heat balance, energy flows, material flows, and since the 1990s this visual model has been used in life-cycle assessment of products.
[src:sankey-diagrams/sankey-diagram] One of the most famous Sankey diagrams is Charles Minard's Map of Napoleon's Russian Campaign of 1812.
[src:sankey-diagrams/sankey-diagram] It is a flow map, overlaying a Sankey diagram onto a geographical map.
[src:sankey-diagrams/sankey-diagram] It was created in 1869, predating Sankey's diagram of 1898.
[src:sankey-diagrams/sankey-diagram] Minard had used this form of diagram for visualising flow of goods and transport of people from at least since 1844.
[src:sankey-diagrams/sankey-diagram] Sankey diagrams are often used in fields of science, especially physics.
[src:sankey-diagrams/sankey-diagram] They are used to represent energy inputs, useful output, and wasted output.
[src:sankey-diagrams/sankey-diagram] The US Energy Information Administration (EIA) produces numerous Sankey diagrams annually in its *Annual Energy Review* which illustrate the production and consumption of various forms of energy.
[src:sankey-diagrams/sankey-diagram] The US Department of Energy's Lawrence Livermore Laboratory maintains a site of Sankey diagrams, including US energy flow and carbon flow.
[src:sankey-diagrams/sankey-diagram] Eurostat, the Statistical Office of the European Union, has developed an interactive Sankey web tool to visualise energy data by means of flow diagrams.
[src:sankey-diagrams/sankey-diagram] The tool allows the building and customisation of diagrams by playing with different options (country, year, fuel, level of detail).
[src:sankey-diagrams/sankey-diagram] The International Energy Agency (IEA) created an interactive Sankey web application that details the flow of energy for the entire planet.
[src:sankey-diagrams/sankey-diagram] Users can select specific countries, points of time back to 1990, and modify the arrangement of various flows within the Sankey diagram.
